\begin_layout Standard
Richardson was optimistic because he classified weather prediction as a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

marching
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 problem (or hyperbolic,
 in PDE terms),
 with information propagating from the initial conditions and from the boundaries,
 as opposed to a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

jury
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 problem,
 in which 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

jurymen
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 sitting at the boundary must all agree simultaneously on then solution (elliptic).
 This classification was correct,
 but the fast characteristic speeds of gravity waves,
 means that numerical methods for solving elliptic problems are beneficial for solving the primitive equations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Finite Differences
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Rich22"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 used centered finite differences,
 knowing them to give second-order accuracy (error are proportional to the square of the grid spacing,
 so as resolution increases,
 errors drop quadratically).
 He used a leapfrog method in time,
 which he described as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

step-over
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 To illustrate this method,
 we can consider the solution of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 equation in just one spatial dimension,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 which is the one-dimensional linear-advection equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial t}+u\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial x}=0.\label{eq:linAdvect1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

If we store values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 on a grid in an array,
 indexed by 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{j}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 at position 
\begin_inset Formula $j\Delta x$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x$
\end_inset

 is the grid spacing.
 Then we can make the second-order,
 centered approximation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial x}\bigg|_{j}=\frac{\theta_{j+1}-\theta_{j-1}}{2\Delta x}.\label{eq:CS}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We also define 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta^{(n)}$
\end_inset

 to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 at time level 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 which is at time 
\begin_inset Formula $n\Delta t$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

 is the time step.
 We can make a similar centered approximation for the rate of change:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial t}\bigg|^{(n)}=\frac{\theta^{(n+1)}-\theta^{(n-1)}}{2\Delta t}.\label{eq:CT}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Equations (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CS"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CT"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) can be substituted into (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linAdvect1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) to give an equation for the next time level based on old values:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\theta_{j}^{(n+1)}=\theta_{j}^{(n-1)}-\frac{u\Delta t}{\Delta x}\left(\theta_{j+1}^{(n)}-\theta_{j-1}^{(n)}\right).\label{eq:CTCSadvect}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This is the explicit,
 centered in time,
 centered in space (CTCS) advection scheme (explicit meaning that the solution at the next time level is found from existing solutions).
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Rich22"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 described a few alternatives for what to do at the very first time step,
 when you do not know values from two previous time levels,
 only one.
 This cost effective scheme is not used much anymore as it generates solutions with oscillations,
 which will be demonstrated in the following exercise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Exercise:
 Numerical Solution of the Linear Advection Equation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Ex_CTCSadvection"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Solve the linear advection equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linAdvect1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) using the centered in time,
 centered in space scheme (CTCS,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CTCSadvect"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 Use a periodic domain 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in[0,1)$
\end_inset

 of 40 points.
 Test the code using the initial conditions
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\theta\left(x,0\right)=\begin{cases}
\frac{1}{2}\left(1-\cos\frac{2\pi\left(x-0.1\right)}{0.3}\right) & \text{for }x\in\left[0.1,0.4\right]\\
1 & \text{for }x\in\left[0.7,0.9\right]\\
0 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Instead of having variables for 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x$
\end_inset

 in your code,
 you can substitute in the Courant number:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c=\frac{u\Delta t}{\Delta x}.\label{eq:Courant}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Set the Courant number to be 0.4 and run for 10 time steps.
 You can compare with the analytic solution
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\theta\left(x,t\right)=\theta\left(x-ut,0\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Plot the solution at a few consecutive time steps.
 What can you say about the part of the solution that started from the smooth initial conditions?
 What do the discontinuities do to the solution?
 Why?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Next try setting the Courant number to be 1.1 and plot the solution after 3,
 4 and 5 time steps.
 What is happening now?
 Why?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Using CTCS,
 oscillations are generated where the initial conditions are discontinuous,
 even when the Courant number is below one.
 A solution is to use a spatial discretisation that takes information from upwind only,
 not from downwind.
 The first-order accurate,
 forward in time,
 backward in space (FTBS) scheme will always give smooth solutions for Courant numbers less than one (and for 
\begin_inset Formula $u>0$
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\theta_{j}^{(n+1)}=\theta_{j}^{(n)}-\frac{u\Delta t}{\Delta x}\left(\theta_{j}^{(n)}-\theta_{j-1}^{(n)}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Code up FTBS and compare the solutions with CTCS.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solutions of this exercise fit with the key take away message is that no numerical method is perfect,
 but the numerical models are useful.
 CTCS is more accurate than FTBS but the solutions can contain oscillations,
 which are not generated by FTBS.
 Both schemes are chap but unstable for Courant numbers greater than one.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Taming Fast Waves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Jule 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Char48"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 explained why Richardson's forecast produced such wild results.
 The primitive equations (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:mom"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:theta"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) include the representation of some fast waves:
 acoustic (sound) waves and gravity waves.
 Deep gravity waves,
 in which large regions of the atmosphere move up and down under the influence of gravity (like waves on the surface of the ocean) can propagate horizontally at similar speed to acoustic waves.
 Fast waves do not carry much meteorological information,
 but they can dominate the numerical stability of weather models if not handled properly.
 The simplest numerical methods are explicit.
 This means that solutions for the next time level are found from previous solutions.
 The combination of an explicit method and local finite differences means that time steps have to be small to avoid unstable oscillations;
 waves cannot travel more than about one grid box in one time step to avoid instability.
 Charney pointed out that aerodynamics had become tractable,
 in part by assuming that the air is close to incompressible,
 so the continuity equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:cont"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) is simplified:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}=0\implies\frac{D\rho}{Dt}=0\label{eq:ico}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which filters out acoustic waves.
 This is not useful for weather prediction because air density varies by orders of magnitude between the surface and the stratosphere.
 Also,
 numerical solutions including (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ico"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) are more difficult because you cannot just march forward;
 you have to find solutions for the components of the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 that satisfy the momentum equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:mom"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) and simultaneously satisfy (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ico"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 The acoustic wave speed has actually been made infitite!
 Charney's solution will be described in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:ellipticSolutions"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 First,
 attempt this exercise exploring time step restrictions due to fast waves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Example:
 Numerical Solution of the Shallow Water Equations
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:solveSW"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The primitive equations can be simplified and averaged in the vertical to produce the shallow water equations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{D\mathbf{u}}{Dt}+2\bm{\Omega}\times\mathbf{u} & =-g\nabla h\label{eq:SWu_vec}\\
\frac{Dh}{Dt} & =-h\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}\label{eq:SWh_vec}
\end{align}

\end_inset

If we consider a local tangent plane to the sphere with 
\begin_inset Formula $g=|\mathbf{g}|$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}=(u,v)$
\end_inset

 then the shallow water equations can be written
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{Du}{Dt}-fv & =-g\frac{\partial h}{\partial x}\label{eq:SWu}\\
\frac{Dv}{Dt}+fu & =-g\frac{\partial h}{\partial y}\label{eq:SWv}\\
\frac{Dh}{Dt} & =-h\left(\frac{\partial u}{\partial y}+\frac{\partial v}{\partial y}\right)\label{eq:SWh}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the Coriolis parameter,
 
\begin_inset Formula $f=2\Omega\sin\phi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is the latitude.
 In order to represent only gravity waves,
 without advection,
 these equations are linearised by replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $H+h$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is uniform in space and time and 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v,h$
\end_inset

 are assumed small so that 
\begin_inset Formula $D/Dt$
\end_inset

 is replaced by 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial/\partial t$
\end_inset

.
 Just considering one spatial dimension and ignoring rotation (
\begin_inset Formula $f=0$
\end_inset

) gives a one-dimensional wave equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{\partial u}{\partial t} & =-g\frac{\partial h}{\partial x}\label{eq:linSWu}\\
\frac{\partial h}{\partial t} & =-H\frac{\partial u}{\partial x}\label{eq:linSWh}
\end{align}

\end_inset

which has gravity wave speed 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{gH}$
\end_inset

.
 If the mean fluid depth,
 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

,
 is,
 for example,
 the height of the troposphere,
 around 10
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

km,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\sim10\text{ m/s}$
\end_inset

 then the gravity wave speed is 316
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m/s,
 close to the speed of sound which is around 343
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m/s.
 The linearised shallow water equations can be solved explicitly using finite differences on a staggered grid,
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 stored at alternating locations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "an excellent choice made by"
key "Rich22"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{h_{j}^{(n+1)}-h_{j}^{(n)}}{\Delta t} & =-H\frac{u_{j+1/2}^{(n)}-u_{j-1/2}^{(n)}}{\Delta x}\label{eq:linSWh_FB_C}\\
\frac{u_{j+1/2}^{(n+1)}-u_{j+1/2}^{(n)}}{\Delta t} & =-g\frac{h_{j+1}^{(n+1)}-h_{j}^{(n+1)}}{\Delta x}\label{eq:linSWu_FB_C}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

 is the time step and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the time level number so that 
\begin_inset Formula $t=n\Delta t$
\end_inset

 is the time.
 The values of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 are stored in arrays indexed by an integer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 The array for 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 at index 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 represents 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 at location 
\begin_inset Formula $j\Delta x$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x$
\end_inset

 is the grid spacing.
 However the array for 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 at grid point 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 will actually represent 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 at location 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(j+1/2\right)\Delta x$
\end_inset

.
 Eqn (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linSWh_FB_C"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) can be rearranged to give 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{j}^{(n+1)}$
\end_inset

 at every grid point using a forward difference in time (the time derivative at time 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is approximated using time 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and the forward time,
 
\begin_inset Formula $n+1$
\end_inset

).
 Once we know 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{j}^{(n+1)}$
\end_inset

,
 this is used to update each 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{j+1/2}^{(n+1)}$
\end_inset

 using an explicit backward time difference.
 The resulting explicit time stepping scheme is called forward-backwards 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Mes77"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and it is stable provided the Courant number associated with gravity waves,
 
\begin_inset Formula $c=\sqrt{gH}\Delta t/\Delta x\le1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Rich22"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 used 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t=6\text{ hours}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x=200\text{ km}$
\end_inset

.
 Could this have been part of the problem with his forecast?
\end_layout

