\begin_layout Subsection
Solving Elliptic Equations
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:ellipticSolutions"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The primitive equations (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:mom"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:theta"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 the linear advection equations (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linAdvect1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) and the shallow water equations (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SWu_vec"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SWh_vec"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) are hyperbolic,
 meaning that information propagates at a finite speed.
 This encouraged Richardson in developing an explicit time-stepping method.
 However,
 the characteristic speeds are so fast that we actually need a numerical method similar to one for solving an elliptic equation.
 By making the incompressible approximation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ico"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) for the primitive equations,
 acoustic waves have infinite speed.
 This converts a time marking problem into a constrain problem,
 and makes the equations elliptic.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Char48"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 derived an elliptic vorticity equation to predict the vertical component of the total vorticity:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eta=\xi+f\label{eq:pv}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=\left(\nabla\times\mathbf{u}\right)\cdot\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 is the vertical component of the (relative) vorticity and planetary rotation,
 or Coriolis parameter,
 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

,
 is the planetary vorticity.
 Vorticity equations can represent slowly evolving weather regimes.
 To derive the barotropic vorticity equation,
 we assume incompressibility and take the curl of the momentum equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SWu_vec"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 apply some vector-calculus identities to get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{D\eta}{Dt}=0\label{eq:baroVortEqn}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

(see the mathematical exercises below).
 This seems wonderfully simple!
 The difficult bit comes is calculating the velocity from the vorticity,
 which is exactly the kind of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

jurymen
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 problem that Richardson wanted to avoid.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Char48"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 realised that some such elliptic solution was essential for avoiding severe time-step restrictions.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Char49"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 knew that weather forecasters relied mostly on charts of pressure to predict the weather.
 It should not be necessary to solve the full primitive equations,
 whose initialisation relies on accurate knowledge of winds,
 density and temperature.
 The wind is close to geostrophic balance,
 which means that,
 in the momentum equation,
 the Coriolis term approximately balances horizontal pressure gradients,
 and the wind flows along isobars,
 rather than down pressure gradients:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{cccc}
u\approx-\frac{1}{\rho f}\frac{\partial p}{\partial y},\ \  & v\approx\frac{1}{\rho f}\frac{\partial p}{\partial x},\ \  & w\approx0 & \text{ or }\mathbf{u}=\mathbf{k}\times\frac{\nabla p}{\rho f}\end{array}.\label{eq:geoBalance}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Therefore the wind flows anti-clockwise,
 or cyclonically,
 around low pressure in the Northern hemisphere and clockwise around anti-cyclones.
 The winds advect the pressure,
 making it evolve slowly,
 making the weather predictable.
 However geostrophic balance cannot be used to predict the weather.
 Geostrophic balance (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:geoBalance"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) implies incompressibility and,
 substituting (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:geoBalance"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) into the momentum equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:mom"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) results in the wind and other variables never changing.
 This is a persistence forecast - the weather tomorrow will be the same as today.
 We don't need equations to make a persistence forecast.
 So it seems that we need need some way to ignore the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

entirely irrelevant gravity motions
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 without assuming incompressibility or exact geostrophic balance.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "CFvN50"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 made the first numerical weather predictions by finding a pressure level in the atmosphere,
 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}$
\end_inset

,
 where horizontal divergence is smallest.
 The equations are then formulated on this pressure surface,
 which has geopotential height,
 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "CFvN50"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 used 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}=500\text{ hPa}$
\end_inset

 and,
 to this day,
 much weather data is reported on the 
\begin_inset Formula $500\text{ hPa}$
\end_inset

 surface and ECMWF use the height of the 
\begin_inset Formula $500\text{ hPa}$
\end_inset

 surface,
 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{500}$
\end_inset

,
 to verify their forecasts.
 Geostrophically balanced winds can be written in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{v}=-\frac{g}{f}\mathbf{k}\times\nabla z\label{eq:geoBalanceZ}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is the horizontal component of the wind.
 Hence the two equations to be solved for the simplest weather prediction are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{D\eta}{Dt} & =0, & g\nabla\cdot\frac{1}{f}\nabla z & =\xi\label{eq:baroVortGeoVort}
\end{align}

\end_inset

to predict total vorticity,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

,
 and geopotential height,
 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 In these equations the fast wave are eliminated,
 not because they are irrelevant,
 but because they can dominate numerical stability while contributing little to large scale weather patterns.
\end_layout

