\begin_layout Subsection
Elliptic Solutions of Hyperbolic Equations – the semi-implicit method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:ellipticSolutions"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 described approximations of the hyperbolic primitive equations (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:mom"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:theta"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) by the elliptic vorticity equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:baroVortEqn"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 The real atmosphere is compressible,
 with finite speed acoustic and gravity waves and non-hydrostatic motions,
 so for the most accurate weather forecasts,
 all of these processes need to be included,
 but without the time step being limited by the speed of the fast waves.
 This is where semi-implicit time stepping comes in.
 Rather than just simplifying the equations,
 the equations are written as corrections to simplified equations,
 so that the simplified,
 linear parts can be solved implicitly,
 leaving the corrections,
 which may be non-linear,
 or just other slow terms,
 to be solved explicitly.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can solve the non-linear shallow water equations (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SWu_vec"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SWh_vec"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) implicitly for gravity waves and explicitly for advection and Coriolis,
 using first-order accurate time stepping:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{\mathbf{u}^{(n+1)}-\mathbf{u}^{(n)}}{\Delta t}+\mathbf{u}^{(n)}\mathbf{\cdot}\nabla\mathbf{u}^{(n)}+2\bm{\Omega}\times\mathbf{u}^{(n)} & =-g\nabla h^{(n+1)}\label{eq:uSI}\\
\frac{h^{(n+1)}-h^{(n)}}{\Delta t}+\mathbf{u}^{(n)}\mathbf{\cdot}\nabla h^{(n)} & =-h^{(n)}\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}^{(n+1)}\label{eq:hSI}
\end{align}

\end_inset

with the terms involved in gravity-wave propagation (in the linearised equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linSWu"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linSWh"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) treated implicitly,
 using the new time level.
 Variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 both consist of arrays of values over a grid,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{(n+1)}$
\end_inset

 is needed to update 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}^{(n+1)}$
\end_inset

 is needed to update 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

.
 To proceed,
 we split 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}^{(n+1)}$
\end_inset

 from (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:uSI"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) into its explicit and implicit parts and substitute this into (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:hSI"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathbf{u}^{(n+1)} & =\mathbf{u}^{\prime}-\Delta tg\nabla h^{(n+1)}\label{eq:backS}\\
\text{where }\mathbf{u}^{\prime} & =\mathbf{u}^{(n)}-\Delta t\left\{ \mathbf{u}^{(n)}\mathbf{\cdot}\nabla\mathbf{u}^{(n)}+2\bm{\Omega}\times\mathbf{u}^{(n)}\right\} \label{eq:uPrimeEqn}\\
\implies\frac{h^{(n+1)}-h^{(n)}}{\Delta t} & -\Delta tgh^{(n)}\nabla^{2}h^{(n+1)}=-\mathbf{u}^{(n)}\mathbf{\cdot}\nabla h^{(n)}-h^{(n)}\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}^{\prime}.\label{eq:hEqn}
\end{align}

\end_inset

The first step is to calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 explicitly from (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:uPrimeEqn"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 Eqn (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:hEqn"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) appears to be an elliptic equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 and is sometimes called the pressure equation or a Helmholtz equation.
 All of the unknown values of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 can be put into an array.
 The discretisation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla^{2}h$
\end_inset

 can be represented as a matrix multiplied by this array.
 Then this matrix equation can be solved to find the array of all of the 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 values.
 The final step is the back-substitution (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:backS"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 to calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}^{(n+1)}$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 and the new values of 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{(n+1)}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Exercise:
 Semi-implicit Solution of the Shallow Water Equations
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "ex:SI_SWE"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This exercise builds on the code written in exercise 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "ex:explicitSWE"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 to solve the linearised shallow water equations (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linSWu"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linSWh"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) explicitly,
 which led to time step restrictions.
 The first task is to solve the linearise,
 one-dimensional equations implicitly,
 then to add the non-linear terms and solve semi-implicitl#y.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The explicit solution of the shallow water equations on a staggered grid is in eqns (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linSWh_FB_C"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linSWu_FB_C"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 This will be converted to an implicit method by replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{(n)}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{(n+1)}$
\end_inset

 on the right hand side of (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linSWh_FB_C"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Re-write eqn (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linSWu_FB_C"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) with just 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{j+1/2_{1}}^{(n+1)}$
\end_inset

 on the left.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Re-write eqn (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linSWh_FB_C"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) with just 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{j}^{(n+1)}$
\end_inset

 on the left and 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{j}^{(n)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{j\pm1/2}^{(n+1)}$
\end_inset

 on the right.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Substitute the equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{j+1/2_{1}}^{(n+1)}$
\end_inset

 into the equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{j}^{(n+1)}$
\end_inset

 .
 Rearrange to get terms involving just 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{(n+1)}$
\end_inset

 on the left and terms at time 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 on the right.
 Write this in terms of the gravity wave Courant number,
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c_{g}=\frac{\sqrt{gH}\Delta t}{\Delta x}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
This can now be expressed as a matrix equation for the vector of all values of 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{(n+1)}$
\end_inset

.
 Work out the matrix coefficients,
 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ij}$
\end_inset

,
 for row 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 Of these,
 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{j-1,j}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{j,j}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{j+1,j}$
\end_inset

 will be non-zero.
 Assume periodic boundary conditions so that the matrix also has non-zero coefficients in the top right and bottom left corners.
 Write code to create this matrix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Write code to calculate an array for the right hand side of the matrix equation.
 
\end_layout

