\begin_layout Enumerate
Test your implicit code by running the same test cases as you ran for the explicit code.
 The solutions should be similar for gravity wave Courant numbers less than one and stable for larger gravity wave Courant numbers.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
This code can now be extended to solve the non-linear,
 one-dimensional shallow water equations with a staggered grid.
 These equations are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial u}{\partial t}+u\frac{\partial u}{\partial x} & =-g\frac{\partial h}{\partial x}\\
\frac{\partial h}{\partial t}+u\frac{\partial h}{\partial x} & =-h\frac{\partial u}{\partial x}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Start by writing down the semi-implicit method for these equations,
 following the mehod in eqns (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:backS"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:hEqn"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We will assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $u>0$
\end_inset

 everywhere,
 for all time.
 This allows us to use a stable upwind approximation for the advection terms.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 can be calculated as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u_{j+1/2}^{\prime}=u_{j+1/2}^{(n)}-\Delta t\ u_{j+1/2}^{(n)}\frac{u_{j+1/2}^{(n)}-u_{j-1/2}^{(n)}}{\Delta x}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In exercise 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Ex_CTCSadvection"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we used a centered in space approximation for advection,
 which lead to oscillations in the solution.
 This upwind approximation,
 with information for calculating 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial u/\partial x$
\end_inset

 coming only from upwind,
 leads to smooth solutions but it is less accurate.
 Using the approximation 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{j}=\frac{1}{2}\left(u_{j-1/2}+u_{j+1/2}\right)$
\end_inset

,
 write down the upwind approximation for the term 
\begin_inset Formula $u\frac{\partial h}{\partial x}$
\end_inset

 at location 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Write down the approximation for the term 
\begin_inset Formula $h\frac{\partial u^{\prime}}{\partial x}$
\end_inset

 at location 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Work out the matrix coefficients for the matrix equation.
 Gravity wave speeds will no longer be uniform,
 so it may not be helpful to define these coefficients in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{g}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Code up a non-linear shallow water equation solver.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Start by testing the code using the same parameters as before but adding a constant to all of the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 so that they never go negative.
 Once this is working,
 modify your upwind discretisation so that it uses forward in space (rather than backward in space) wherever 
\begin_inset Formula $u<0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Test the code using asymptotics:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Use coefficients that give a large gravity wave Courant number and a small Courant number.
 This will make the equations behave close to the linear system.
 Check that,
 as you reduce the ratio of Courant number to gravity wave Courant number,
 the results become more and more similar to the linearised solver.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Set 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 to zero.
 Then,
 initialising with 
\begin_inset Formula $u=1$
\end_inset

 everywhere will mean that the height equation should give identical results to the linear advection equation solved using FTBS.
 Altenatively,
 initilising with uniform 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 will mean that the 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 equation becomes Burger's equation,
 and the results should be identical to a solution of Burger's equation solved with FTBS.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
The key take away from this section is that semi-implicit methods remove fast wave time step limits,
 but the solutions may be less accurate and large linear equation solvers are needed,
 which can be expensive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
A Golden Era of Numerical Weather Prediction:
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\size normal
Three Dimensional Solutions on Mainframe Computers
\series medium
 
\series default
\size default

\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A Golden Era of Numerical Weather Prediction
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the 1950s to the turn of the century,
 models of the atmosphere became ever more realistic and numerical weather prediction became,
 first,
 possible,
 and then ever more accurate and valuable.
 Looking back,
 the progress seemed easier then.
 The interval between the first paper describing a new method and an operational model was only a few years,
 and the papers had fewer authors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the 1950s,
 numerical models were still plagued by oscillations and instabilities that were not understood.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Smag58"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 solved the the primitive equations in three dimensions (with just two vertical levels).
 But the paper mostly discusses causes of instability and no plots of numerical results are presented,
 suggesting that there was little realism in the results.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Phil59"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 simulated the entire northern hemisphere with one horizontal layer,
 with a 24 hour simulation taking 84 minutes.
 Like 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Rich22"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Phil59"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 was still blaming grid-scale oscillations on the lack of smoothness in the initial conditions,
 rather than blaming the numerical methods.
 However in reality,
 turbulent diffusion is tiny above the surface boundary layer,
 which is only about a kilometre deep.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Smag63"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 created a two-layer model between the equator and 64
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
o
\end_layout

\end_inset

N which he was able to run for 60 days,
 simulating baroclinic instability,
 poleward heat transport and a Hadley circulation,
 with some realism.
 Grid-scale oscillations were controlled using eddy viscosity to mimic the effects of turbulent diffusion.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Smag63"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 mentioned Arakawa's emerging work on energy conserving methods which would prove revolutionary in atmosphere and ocean modelling.
 The first UK Met Office numerical forecast was produced in 1965 on a Comet computer 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "MOhistory26"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 which solved a three-level vorticity equation and used geostrophically balanced initial winds in order to avoid noisy initial conditions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "BW61"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Arakawa's work was necessary in order to move from vorticity equations to the stable solution of momentum equations,
 which is described in the next section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Arakawa's Numerics
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:ArakawaGrids"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Arakawa grids are a selection of options of where variables are stored on a grid,
 which give different compromises in terms of simplicity,
 accurate wave propagation and representation of geostrophic balance.
 They are still hotly debated and there is no overall best option.
\end_layout

