\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "AL77"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 described the numerical methods used on the UCLA general circulation model;
 a landmark in the development of stable and accurate numerical methods for the atmosphere,
 a 92 page article that is still being cited (3,538 citations in total,
 with over 100 citations every year since 2014).
 The model is three dimensional with 12 vertical levels,
 
\begin_inset Formula $72\times45$
\end_inset

 grid points in the horizontal and a time step of 6 minutes.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "AL77"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is best known for the description of the Arakawa grids - 5 arrangements of prognostic variables on a grid.
 They wrote the momentum equation,
 for the horizontal velocity,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

,
 in vector-invariant form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{D\mathbf{v}}{Dt}+f\mathbf{k}\times\mathbf{v}+\frac{1}{\rho}\nabla_{h}p+\nabla_{h}K=\mathbf{F}_{h}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $K=\frac{1}{2}|\mathbf{v}|^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the kinetic energy,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}_{h}$
\end_inset

 is the horizontal component of the frictional force and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{h}$
\end_inset

 is the horizontal component of the gradient.
 Solving the vector-invariant form enables exact energy conservation,
 with losses in gravitiational potential being exactly transferred to kinetic energy,
 and back.
 The Arakawa grids A-E are shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Arakawa-A-E"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The advantages and dis-advantages of these grids can best be seen in terms of the linearised shallow water equations.
 The one-dimensional linearised shallow water equations without Coriolis are (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linSWu"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linSWh"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 The two-dimensional linearised shallow water equations can be obtained by replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $D/Dt$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial/\partial t$
\end_inset

 in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SWu"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SWh"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) and replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 with the constant,
 uniform average height,
 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

,
 on the right hand side of (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SWh"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 As was investigated in example 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:solveSW"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 if all variables are located together,
 as in the A-grid,
 then the pressure (or height) gradients needed to update the velocity,
 are calculated over three grid points,
 missing the central location (eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linSWu_FB_A"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) and the divergence needed to update the height in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SWh"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) is calculated over three points in each direction,
 missing the central location (eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linSWh_FB_A"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 This omission of the central location means that grid-scale oscillations can develop – oscillations in 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 can be present which do not lead to height gradients,
 and oscillations in 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 can be present which do not lead to divergence.
 These oscillations are spurious computational modes and make the A-grid problematic for atmospheric modelling.
 Considering the height gradients and the divergence terms of eqns (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SWu"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SWh"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 the C-grid appears to be ideal – compact height gradients in the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-direction (using two points without missing out a central point),
 are centered at the 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 location,
 compact height gradients in the 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

-direction are at the 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 location and the divergence can be calculated at the 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 location without missing any velocities at 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

.
 This means that gravity wave propagation is most accurate and free of computational modes on the C-grid,
 and this grid was chosen by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "AL77"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for the UCLA model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Gravity waves are not the only phenomena being modelled,
 and even in the linearised shallow water equations the Coriolis terms need to be represented accurately.
 If we consider only the rates of change and the Coriolis terms,
 we get equations for inertial oscillations
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{\partial u}{\partial t} & =fv & \frac{\partial v}{\partial t} & =-fu\label{eq:inertialOsc}
\end{align}

\end_inset

which have solutions with air (or water) going round in circles with radius 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{u_{o}^{2}+v_{0}^{2}}$
\end_inset

 and angular frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 In order to model (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:inertialOsc"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) most accurately,
 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 should be at the same locations on the grid,
 otherwise spatial averaging will be needed.
 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 are at the same location for grids A,
 B and E but not C or D.
 The UK Met Office chose the B-grid for their first unified model of weather and climate 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "CD91"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 For the C-grid,
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 stored at grid point 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(i,j\right)$
\end_inset

,
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $x=i\Delta x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y=j\Delta y$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 will be stored at 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(i+1/2,j\right)$
\end_inset

 and updated with averaging for the Coriolis term:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
u_{i+1/2,j}^{(n+1)} & =u_{i+1/2,j}^{(n)}\\
 & +\Delta t\left\{ f\frac{v_{i,j-1/2}+v_{i+1,j-1/2}+v_{i,j+1/2}+v_{i+1,j+1/2}}{4}-g\frac{h_{i+1,j}-h_{i,j}}{\Delta x}\right\} \nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

This averaging reduces accuracy and enables spurious computational modes at coarse resolution,
 but the accurate representation of gravity waves has proven to be more important for atmospheric modelling.
 This may seem counter intuitive,
 considering that 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "CFvN50"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 described these waves as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

entirely irrelevant gravity motions
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 They are not irrelevant.
 They are the mechanism by which the flow comes into geostrophic balance – if there is a region of high height and no flow along the boundary of the high height,
 then gravity waves will be generated,
 flow will be created and the fluid will move towards geostrophic balance (a process called geostrophic adjustment).
 If gravity waves are filtered then this process is assumed to happen instantaneously.
 It is essential that gravity waves are represented in order to adjust the fluid to geostrophic balance,
 but it is less important to accurately model the speed of gravity waves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The D-grid may appear ideal for representing fluids that are close to geostrophic balance,
 since the terms involved in geostrophic balance are the largest in the momentum equation (for example,
 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is in the same place as the most compact calculation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial p/\partial x$
\end_inset

).
 However these are both terms in the 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 equation,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is at a different location,
 meaning that averaging of large terms is needed for the D-grid.
 The E-grid is the same as the B-grid but rotated by 45
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
o
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

