\begin_layout Subsection
The Spectral Method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The European Centre for Medium Range Weather Forecasts (ECMWF) consistently produces the most accurate global weather forecasts,
 with skill improving at the rate of one day per decade 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "HJV+24"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 ECMWF specialise in forecasts with lead times of one to two weeks.
 Skillfull forecasts at these longer lead times was made possible when they switched from finite differences to the spectral method 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "GJ82,SBJ+89"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 to solve the primitive equations on there sphere.
 Spectral methods have exponential convergence.
 This means that they have the highest possible order of accuracy for the number of grid points.
 This comes at the cost of all to all communication.
 This sounds like a big problem for massively parallel computers.
 ECMWF's spectral model is continuing to scale well – but we do not know how long can this continue,
 when it is competing with methods that communicate only locally.
 The spectral method is also inherently global – it is not suited for local area models,
 and the ECMWF spectral model is only efficient in hydrostatic mode,
 whereas the real atmosphere is non-hydrostatic.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section gives a simple example of a spectral method.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Dur11"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 provides a more general definition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to solve
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial\phi}{\partial t}+F\left(\phi\right)=0\label{eq:generalPDE}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for some function,
 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

,
 we represent 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 as a sum of globally defined basis functions.
 For simplicity,
 we will consider a one-dimensional periodic domain,
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in[-\pi,\pi]$
\end_inset

,
 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 can be represented as a sum of 
\begin_inset Formula $2N+1$
\end_inset

 Fourier modes,
 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{ikx}$
\end_inset

,
 with Fourier coefficients,
 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi\left(x,t\right)=\sum_{k=-N}^{N}a_{k}\left(t\right)e^{ikx}.\label{eq:FourierDecomp}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The initial Fourier coefficients,
 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}\left(t_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

,
 can be found using the orthogonality property of the Fourier modes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}e^{ipx}e^{-iqx}dx=\begin{cases}
2\pi & \text{if }p=q\\
0 & \text{otherwise.}
\end{cases}\label{eq:FourierOrthogonal}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

So if (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FourierDecomp"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) is multiplied by 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-iqx}$
\end_inset

 and integrated between 
\begin_inset Formula $-\pi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

,
 we get equations for the initial Fourier coefficients from the initial conditions:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
a_{k}\left(t_{0}\right) & =\frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}\phi\left(x,t_{0}\right)e^{-ikx}dx\label{eq:FourierTransform}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Eqn (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FourierTransform"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) is a Fourier transform and computers have fast algorithms called ffts (fast Fourier transforms) for calculating Fourier coefficients from evaluations of a function at regularly spaced intervals.
 However to find solutions of (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:generalPDE"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 we need to know how the Fourier coefficients vary in time.
 We need to find each 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 so that when (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FourierDecomp"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) is substituted into (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:generalPDE"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:generalPDE"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) is satisfied as closely as possible.
 For the spectral method 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

as closely as possible
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 means the Galerkin approximation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}\left\{ \frac{\partial\phi}{\partial t}+F\left(\phi\right)\right\} e^{-ikx}dx=0\ \forall k\in-N,...,N.\label{eq:spectralGalerkin}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Substituting (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FourierDecomp"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) into (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:spectralGalerkin"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 using the orthogonality of the Fourier modes and simplifying gives:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
2\pi\frac{da_{k}}{dt}+\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}F\left(\sum_{q=-N}^{N}a_{q}\left(t\right)e^{iqx}\right)e^{-ikx}dx=0.\label{eq:spectralMethod}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

To make progress in evaluating the second part of the integral in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:spectralMethod"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 we need to know 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 We will consider some examples.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Linear Advection using the Spectral Method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Eqn (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:generalPDE"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) becomes the linear advection equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(\phi\right)=u\ \partial\phi/\partial x$
\end_inset

 with a constant,
 uniform wind speed 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

.
 Then (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:spectralMethod"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) simplifies to
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{da_{k}}{dt}=iua_{k}\label{eq:spectralLinearAdvect}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which can be solved either analytically or numerically for each 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}$
\end_inset

,
 starting from the initial conditions,
 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}\left(t_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 from the Fourier transform (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FourierTransform"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Non-linear Advection using the Spectral Method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Eqn (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:generalPDE"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) becomes Burgers equation for non-linear advection for 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(\phi\right)=\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial\phi^{2}}{\partial x}$
\end_inset

.
 Now eqn (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:spectralMethod"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{da_{k}}{dt}+\frac{ik}{2}\sum_{p+q=k}a_{p}\left(t\right)a_{q}\left(t\right)=0\label{eq:spectralBurger}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which can be solved numerically using an ODE solver,
 starting from the initial conditions,
 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}\left(t_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

