\begin_layout Section
The Pole Problem and Parallel Computing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section explains why the choice of discretisation is dictated as much by computer architecture as by numerical analysis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the 1970s to 1990s,
 numerical weather prediction used mainframe computers such as the vector-parallel Cray computers.
 Parallel means that they had more than one processor,
 running in parallel.
 In the 1990s,
 Crays had 2,
 4,
 8 or of 16 processors.
 The atmosphere was decomposed into a domains,
 one for each processor,
 and the equations of motion were solved separately on each domain,
 with communication at the boundaries.
 Each processor operated on a vector of numbers at the same time,
 with vector lengths typically of 8,
 16,
 32 or 64.
 The 1970s to 1990s was a time of rapid increases in computational power,
 with gains in efficiency due to increases in vector length and number of processors 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "eg."
key "BDI+95"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 With this moderate parallelisation and moderate domain size,
 performance was not limited by parallel communication or memory band width.
 These were the day of Moore's law,
 with computational power doubling every two years,
 which enabled steady increases in model resolution without drastic changes to the numerical methods or algorithms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even in the 1990s,
 vector-parallel machines were being replaced by machines with far more,
 cheaper,
 off the shelf microprocessors.
 Into the 2000s and 2010s,
 weather prediction models scaled on these pure parallel machines,
 with the atmosphere being decomposed into more and more,
 smaller domains,
 all with overlapping halo regions at their edges,
 where information is exchanged.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following the successful use of semi-implicit,
 semi-Lagrangian (SISL) modelling at ECMWF 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "RTS+95"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 the UK Met Office replaced their explicit B-grid model with a semi-implicit,
 semi-Lagrangian C-grid model 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "CDM+97,DCM+05"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 SISL enables excellent weather and climate prediction on latitude-longitude grids since SISL overcomes time step restrictions near the poles.
 At time of writing the operational model used by the UK Met Office,
 EndGame,
 still uses SISL on a latutide-longitude grid,
 and has consistently been one of the most accurate models,
 usually second only to ECMWF 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "eg."
key "HJV+24"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 However the combination of further parallelisation,
 increased resolution and the convergence of meridians towards the poles means that parallelisation progress on latitude-longitude grids is stuck – more processors are added,
 domains get smaller and the code does not run faster or even at the same speed using higher resolution.
 It is not possible to overcome the large amount of communication that must be done near the poles to make latitude-longitude usable at modern high resolutions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Modern Parallel Computers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The current ECMWF supercomputer has 7,680 AMD Epyc compute nodes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ECMWFcomputer26"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 which are similar to the CPUs on desktop or laptop computers.
 The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) uses a cluster of 63,840 cores,
 including CPUs and GPUs (graphical processing units),
 since GPUs are now being used to provide vector calculations which are faster that the one at a time calculations on each CPU core 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "NOAA_HERA26"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The UK Met Office has recently moved to cloud based computing provided my Microsoft's Azure service,
 which gives them flexibility on how many and what type of core they use.
 However the weather prediction models can rarely use the whole of any modern supercomputer because,
 even if the whole computer were available,
 the model would not be able to scale well enough to use so many processors efficiently;
 processors would end up spending too much time waiting for data from neighbouring processors.
 This is the parallel scaling problem.
 The current Met Office model,
 on a latitude-longitude grid,
 can use thousands of processors efficiently,
 but not tens of thousands 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "WBB+17"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 which is needed for the most accurate,
 highest resolution solutions.
 In order to scale in parallel on 10s or 100s of thousands of processor,
 quasi-uniform meshes of the sphere are needed,
 which do not have convergence of points towards the poles,
 or any other locations.
 The next Met Office model,
 LFRic,
 uses a quasi-uniform mesh and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "BBD+26"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 demonstrated scaling to 383,216 CPUs on ARCHER2,
 which uses AMD Epyc compute nodes.
 LFRic should be operational by the time you read this.
 More on LFRic in sections 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:FFSL"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:mixedFEM"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Meshes of the Sphere
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A latitude-longitude grid (fig 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:grids"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 left) is the most obvious way to decompose the atmosphere and solve the equations of motion using,
 for example,
 finite differences,
 and models using latitude-longitude grids are producing accurate weather predictions and informative climate projections to this day.
 The current Met Office global weather prediction uses a grid of 
\begin_inset Formula $2,560\times1,920$
\end_inset

 points 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "MO_UM26"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 which gives grid boxes of size 
\begin_inset Formula $15\text{ km}\times10\text{ km}$
\end_inset

 around the equator but at each pole,
 the grid boxes will still be 10
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

km in the north-south direction but less than 25
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m in the east-west direction!
 In order to get smooth solutions over the poles,
 all of the 2,560 grid points in the east-west direction around each pole will need to be in communication,
 despite being on different processors.
 This inevitably slows the simulation down.
 At modern resolutions,
 latitude-longitude grids are not merely inefficient,
 they are a fundamental barrier to scalability.
 This century,
 weather prediction has been moving away from the latitude-longitude grid due (in part) to the parallel scaling bottle necks as the number of parallel processors increases.
 Even before parallel scaling was a critical bottleneck,
 ECMWF moved to a reduced grid,
 which coarser resolution towards the poles 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "HS91"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 in order to save in computation time and memory requirement.
 This was more straightforward using a spectral model as they key point was to use few wavenumbers close to the poles.
 
\end_layout

