caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 is quasi-uniform – all of the grid boxes have similar dimensions and a low aspect ratio.
 However the mesh is not orthogonal – local co-ordinate systems for each of the cube faces are not at right angles.
 A cubed sphere can be constructed to be orthogonal,
 but then resolution clusters towards the cube corners,
 removing the quasi-uniform property.
 Meshes of polygons (such a the hexagonal icosahedron,
 right of fig 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:grids"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) and meshes of triangles are quasi-uniform and can be constructed to be orthogonal.
 For these meshes,
 orthogonality needs a different definition.
 The triangular icosahedron is the dual of the hexagonal icosahedron.
 This means that if you put a point at the centre of each polygon of the hexagonal icosahedron,
 and join the points over the edges,
 then you get the triangular icosahedron.
 If the mesh and its dual have edges that cross at right angles,
 then the mesh is orthogonal.
 Orthogonal meshes have advangages in terms of accuracy and efficiency,
 but there are other considerations,
 such as the skewness – do the edges of the dual grids bisect each other or cross not at the edge centres 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Wel14"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 There are compromises to be made when optimising icosahedral meshes for numerical methods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Numerical Methods for the Future
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The numerical methods developed for latitude-longitude grids,
 such as semi-implicit,
 semi-Lagrangian and the Arakawa C-grid have superb accuracy and are efficient as long as the domain is not decomposed onto too many parallel processors,
 which is needed on modern computers.
 Moving to alternative meshes,
 such as the cubed sphere or icosahedra (fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:grids"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 means that more complex numerical methods are needed in order to retain accuracy.
 This section describes some more complex spatial discretisation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Finite volumes
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:FV"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In their simplest form,
 on structured grids (such as latitude-longitude),
 the finite volume method is similar to the finite difference method.
 Important features of finite volume methods are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Averages of computed quantities are stored in finite volume cells and the averages change based on fluxes of the quantity over the surface faces of the cell.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The finite volume cells can be any tessellating shape.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The total of the computed quantity is conserved.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to solve an advection equation with the finite volume method,
 the equation must first be written in flux form,
 with everything that varies inside a divergence term.
 We can start with the continuity equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:cont"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) which can be re-written in flux form using vector-calculus identities
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial\rho}{\partial t}+\mathbf{u}\cdot\rho+\rho\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}=0\implies\frac{\partial\rho}{\partial t}+\nabla\cdot\left(\mathbf{u}\rho\right)=0.\label{eq:contFlux}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The finite volume method predicts density weighted volume averages (for example the mass of an atmospheric constituent,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

) in each cell.
 We can derive an equation for the rate of change of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\phi$
\end_inset

 using the continuity equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:contFlux"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 the linear advection equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linAdvect"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) and the chain rule:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{\partial\rho\phi}{\partial t} & =\rho\frac{\partial\phi}{\partial t}+\phi\frac{\partial\rho}{\partial t}\nonumber \\
 & =\rho\left\{ -\mathbf{u}\cdot\nabla\phi\right\} +\phi\left\{ -\nabla\cdot\left(\mathbf{u}\rho\right)\right\} \nonumber \\
\implies\frac{\partial\rho\phi}{\partial t} & +\nabla\cdot\left(\rho\mathbf{u}\phi\right)=0.\label{eq:linAdvectFlux}
\end{align}

\end_inset

To simplify the definition of the finite volume method,
 we will assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is uniform in space and time and that the atmosphere is incompressible:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}=0$
\end_inset

.
 We consider a cell with volume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 and integrate over this volume to find the rate of change of the volume average,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\phi}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial\tilde{\phi}}{\partial t}=\frac{1}{\mathcal{V}}\int_{\mathcal{V}}\frac{\partial\phi}{\partial t}\ dV=-\frac{1}{\mathcal{V}}\int_{\mathcal{V}}\nabla\cdot\left(\mathbf{u}\phi\right)\ dV
\end{equation}

\end_inset

(the last step using the linear advection equation in flux form,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linAdvectFlux"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 We now apply Gauss's divergence theorem to transform the integral to an integral over the surface of the volume:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{\mathcal{V}}\nabla\cdot\left(\mathbf{u}\phi\right)\ dV=\int_{S}\mathbf{u}\phi\cdot\mathbf{dS}\implies\frac{\partial\tilde{\phi}}{\partial t}=-\frac{1}{\mathcal{V}}\int_{S}\phi\mathbf{u}\cdot\mathbf{dS}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is the surface of volume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{dS}$
\end_inset

 is the outward pointing normal vector to the surface.
 If we assume that the volume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 has a discrete number of faces,
 indexed with 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

,
 each with outward pointing normal vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{S}_{f}$
\end_inset

 (with magnitude equal to the face area),
 then the finite volume discretisation of the linear advection equation becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial\tilde{\phi}}{\partial t}=-\frac{1}{\mathcal{V}}\sum_{f}\phi_{f}\mathbf{u}_{f}\cdot\mathbf{S}_{f}\label{eq:FVadvect}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{f}$
\end_inset

 is the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 mapped onto face 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}_{f}\cdot\mathbf{S}_{f}$
\end_inset

 is the volume flux through face 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

,
 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{f}\mathbf{u}_{f}\cdot\mathbf{S}_{f}$
\end_inset

 is the volume flux of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 through face 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 There are countless different finite volume methods and they are distinct in the way that they map volume averages,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\phi}$
\end_inset

,
 onto face averages,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{f}$
\end_inset

.
 In order to solve (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FVadvect"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 the fluxes,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}_{f}\cdot\mathbf{S}_{f}$
\end_inset

,
 must be supplied from elsewhere in the model.
 The fluxes and the face averages,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{f}$
\end_inset

,
 are equal and opposite for the two cells either side of face 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

,
 so what leaves one cell will enter its neighbour,
 which is what makes finite volume methods conservative,
 regardless of how the mapping is done.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Exercise:
 Equivalence of Finite Volume and Finite Difference
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Often,
 on uniform and structured grids,
 finite volume methods can be written as finite difference methods and vice versa.
 Eqn (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CS"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) is a finite difference approximation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\phi/\partial x$
\end_inset

 at grid point 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 If instead we use 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 to index one-dimensional grid boxes,
 with size 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x$
\end_inset

 and edges at locations 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(j\pm1/2\right)\Delta x$
\end_inset

,
 indexed as 
\begin_inset Formula $j\pm1/2$
\end_inset

,
 then we can derive a finite volume approximation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\cdot\left(\mathbf{u}\phi\right)$
\end_inset

.
 If we assume that the velocity,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}=(u,0,0)$
\end_inset

 is uniform in space and time and if we use the centred mapping
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi_{j+1/2}=\frac{1}{2}\left(\tilde{\phi}_{j}+\tilde{\phi}_{j+1}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

show that the finite volume method gives the same approximation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\phi/\partial x$
\end_inset

 as the centred finite difference method (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CS"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Flux-form Semi-Lagrangian
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:FFSL"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The semi-Lagrangian method,
 described in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:SL"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 has played a large role in enabling unprecedented accuracy in weather prediction.
 However standard (interpolating) semi-Lagrangian is not conservative – the total mass of the quantity advected can change just because it is being advected.
 This is not correct and makes semi-Lagrangian unsuitable for climate prediction and for the next generation in weather prediction.
 A popular solution is flux-form semi-Lagrangian (FFSL),
 which is a type of finite volume advection scheme.
 FFSL is used in FV3 by the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "NOAA,"
key "HCP+21"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 in the NCAR Community Atmosphere Model,
 CAM-FV 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "NRC+10"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 in the Japanese NICAM 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Miu07b"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 in the German ICON model 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ZRR+15,ICON26"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and will be used in the next Met Office model,
 LFRic 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "BK25"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rather than interpolating onto a departure point,
 in FFSL,
 interpolation is onto the volume of air that sweeps through each face in a time step (fig 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:SL"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 right).
 Then,
 using the finite volume method,
 the contents of each cell is updated based on the amounts that enter and leave at each face.
 FFSL is therefore conservative.
 FFSL can be made to be stable and accurate for large time steps by mapping onto the swept volume over multiple cells upwind of each face.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
FFSL is used so widely and is so effective,
 that it has been created independently in different institutions and given different names.
 The piecewise parabolic method 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "PPM,"
key "CW84"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 was one of the first FFSL methods,
 and was described as a higher-order Godunov method.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "LLM96"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 described this type of scheme as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

forward in time
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,
 and described how to extend them to two and three dimensions while maintaining conservation and constancy preservation – a field that starts constant should remain constant when advected by a non-divergent velocity field.
 In the same journal issue,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "LR96"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 described a similar scheme and named it 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

flux-form semi-Lagrangian
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 This was the scheme that is still in use in the NOAA model,
 FV3.
 There have been numerous improvements since the 1990s,
 but of particular note is SWIFT 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "BK25"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 which extends the long time step stability,
 conservation and constancy preservation to variable density advection,
 providing the advection scheme for the new Met Office model,
 LFRic.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In many ways,
 PPM and FFSL seem unbeatable.
 The only down side is that,
 in order to achieve efficiency for large time steps,
 the grid must be be regular.
 That means that the grid must consist of (possibly distorted) boxes that are arranged in the Cartesian directions.
 This is because the COSMIC splitting that is used to transform a scheme like PPM from one to two and three dimensions,
 relies on searching for departure points along co-ordinate directions.
 This precludes the use of FFSL with large time steps for icosahedral meshes,
 and means that special measures are needed to handle the corners of the cubed-sphere mesh.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Exercises:
 Finite Volume Solutions of the Advection Equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Starting from the flux-form linear advection equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linAdvectFlux"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 prove constant preservation;
 that if the advected quantity,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

,
 starts uniform,
 then it will stay uniform,
 given the following assumptions:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The density is uniform and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}=0$
\end_inset

 (incompressible flow).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The density is non-uniform and varies according to the continuity equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:contFlux"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}\ne0$
\end_inset

 (compressible flow).
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The Lax-Wendroff advection scheme can be expressed as a FFSL scheme.
 Using the same notation and one-dimensional grid as for the finite difference CTCS scheme (eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CTCSadvect"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 the Lax-Wendroff advection scheme can be written
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\phi_{j}^{(n+1)}-\phi_{j}^{(n)}}{\Delta t} & =-\frac{u_{j+1/2}\phi_{j+1/2}-u_{j-1/2}\phi_{j-1/2}}{\Delta x}\\
\text{where }\phi_{j+1/2} & =\nicefrac{1}{2}\left(1+c\right)\phi_{j}^{(n)}+\nicefrac{1}{2}\left(1-c\right)\phi_{j+1}^{(n)}\\
c & =u\Delta t/\Delta x.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Write code to solve the linear advection equation using Lax-Wendroff and compare with the CTCS solutions found in exercise 
