\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Finite Volume A- and C-grids for unstructured meshes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sections 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:FV"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:FFSL"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 described finite volume methods for solving the linear advection equation,
 which has one dependent variable,
 which is stored as a volume average in each cell.
 Once we have multiple variables that create waves and,
 in particular,
 we are solving the momentum equation for the velocity components,
 we must return to Arakawa's problem of where to store different variables (section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:ArakawaGrids"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 This has added complexity because a finite volume mesh can include cells of arbitrary shapes,
 such as the triangles,
 pentagons and hexagons in icosahedral meshes (fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:grids"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The purest form of finite volume is co-located,
 the A-grid,
 so that the velocity is stored as volume averages in the cells,
 the same as the variables that are advected by the wind.
 This approach is used effectively by NICAM 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "SMT+08"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 which stores all variables apart from vertical velocity in cells.
 Vertical velocity is stored at the top and bottom faces of cells.
 So NICAM uses the A-grid in the horizontal and the C-grid (staggered) in the vertical.
 ECMWF's finite volume model,
 PMAP,
 or FVM,
 currently a research model,
 is fully co-located with all variable stored in cells 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "KDK+19"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and is close to ECMWF's spectral transform model in terms of accuracy and efficiency.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Despite excellent solutions from co-located (A-grid) finite volume models on various grids,
 the A-grid is prone to grid-scale oscillations,
 which can usually be smoothed out with some kind of diffusion or filter.
 This has motivated the development of C-grid discretisations on triangles for the ICON model 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bon04,ZRR+15"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and on hexagons and pentagons for,
 example,
 MPAS 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "TRSK09,SKD+12,RPH+13"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 ICON produces skilful global weather forecasts,
 but the underlying dynamical core is still prone to grid-scale oscillations and requires diffusion.
 It turns out that the C-grid on triangles is not as well behaved as hoped.
 Spurious steady solutions with pressure oscillations between up and down pointing triangles persist because the alternating high and low pressures are in geostrophic balance with winds circulating around each triangle.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Gas11"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 explained that the oscillations on triangles cannot be controlled by the insufficient normal velocity components at the triangle edges,
 and that the hexagonal C-grid performs better.
 MPAS,
 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Model for Prediction Across Scales
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,
 was developed as a global version of the popular WRF model and uses the hexagonal C-grid 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "SKD+12"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 It is free of grid-scale oscillations in height or pressure,
 but spurious grid-scale circulations can appear around the hexagon vertices,
 a manifestation of the Hollingsworth instability 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Gas13"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finite-volume methods for wave equations (such as the A- and C-grid finite voulme methods),
 tend to be low-order accurate – usually up to second-order.
 However,
 despite the smooth,
 well behaved solutions,
 the C-grid on the hexagonal-icosahedron is found to be much less than second-order,
 with a complete loss of convergence with resolution in some situations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "YWM+20"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 who found serious deficiencies in both the A- and C-grids on hexagonal icosahedral meshes.
 This provides a strong motivation to move to more complex numerical methods for quasi-uniform meshes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Spectral Elements
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:SE"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename climate_numFigures/cubedSphereSEM.jpg
	lyxscale 50
	width 100text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A spectral element as part of a cube-sphere mesh from figure 4 from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "LJTN10"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 showing 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

(left) A graphical illustration of the Gauss-Legendre-Lobatto quadrature points (red unfilled circles) in an element (blue boundary) of the HOMME model.
 (right) The mapping of every element onto the sphere.
 Green lines are the boundary of the cubed-sphere faces
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Reproduced with permission from John Wiley and Sons.
 Copyright 2010 by the American Geophysical Union.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:CAMSE"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Spectral elements enables arbitrarily high-order accuracy on a variety of meshes,
 and are extremely efficient on massively parallel computers.
 Fourth-order accurate spectral elements are used in a version of NCAR Community Atmosphere Model,
 CAM-SE 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "NRC+10,ELM+13"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 on a cubed sphere (fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:CAMSE"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 right).
 Considering just the horizontal discretisation in CAM-SE,
 the surface of the Earth is divided into quadrilateral elements.
 The solution is approximated on each element using a basis function which is a two-dimensional,
 third-order polynomial.
 A key advantage of spectral elements is that they use Lagrange interpolation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "WTB+07"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 which means that the basis functions passes through nodes on each element exactly and the weights of each basis function are cheap to compute and avoid global communication.
 By placing these notes at Gauss-Legendre-Lobatto quadrature points (fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:CAMSE"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 left) the order of accuracy is one more than the degree of the polynomial used,
 so the third-order polynomial basis functions give a fourth-order accurate numerical method.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The high-order accuracy of spectral elements,
 and the continuity between elements,
 makes them excellent choices for smoothly varying fields such as pressure,
 but less suitable for fields with more fine scale variability such as clouds and precipitation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "WTB+07"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The spectral element version of CAM produces a similar climate to the finite volume version 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ELM+13"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 but the spectral element version is more efficient on larger super computers and provides more detail at fine resolutions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Spectral elements are continuous Galerkin methods.
 This means that there is a level of continuity between elements and spectral elements are accurate when solutions are smooth.
 The discretisation is symmetric – there is no account taken of which direction is upwind.
 We learned in the exercise 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Ex_CTCSadvection"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 that symmetric discretisations lead to oscillatory solutions when advecting discontinuous fields,
 whereas using upwind information to calculate gradients enables smooth solutions.
