\begin_layout Subsection
Discontinuous Galerkin
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The discontinuous Galerkin method (DG) is similar to the spectral element method (a continuous Galerkin method),
 but discontinuities are allowed between elements.
 Like the finite volume method,
 there are fluxes between elements,
 leading to asymmetry,
 and more upwind information than downwind is used in calculations.
 DG can handle discontinuous fields without the need to introduce artificial diffusion,
 but is is slightly more expensive.
 The cost is offset by the excellent scaling properties on massively parallel computers.
 DG is not currently being used operationally for weather prediction but powerful research models exist such as NUMA-NEPTUNE,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "KG12"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 developed at the Naval Postgraduate School and DG-COSMO 
